@*
    In-sheet unit-conversion prompt for the recipe ingredient editor (C10 early UX, plantry-c9s2;
    four-field equation editor, plantry-qno9).

    Shown when the author picks a cross-dimension unit (e.g. "cup" for a product catalogued in "g"):
    the Alpine $watch on draft.unitId detects the gap live via OnGetCheckConversionAsync and sets
    draft.needsConversion = true. This partial renders the inline ask as a two-sided equation so the
    author can state the fact they already know ("1 kg = 8 cups") verbatim, instead of being forced to
    express it as "1 {recipeUnit} = ___ {stockDefault}" and do the arithmetic themselves.

    The equation, each dropdown constrained to ONE axis:

        [amount] [ unit ▾ ]   =   [amount] [ unit ▾ ]
          LEFT: product STOCK dimension   RIGHT: recipe-line dimension
          (units from draft.stockUnits)   (units from draft.recipeUnits)

    Because the two axes always differ (that is exactly why the prompt appears), the pair ALWAYS
    bridges — a same-dimension "nonsense" entry is impossible by construction, so there is NO live
    non-bridging guard. The server computes factor = rightAmount / leftAmount, from = left unit,
    to = right unit; UnitConverter bridges same-dimension hops on each side and in both directions, so
    storing (kg → cup, 8) resolves a recipe in cups (or tbsp) against stock in g.

    Prefill keeps the common path to a single keystroke: LEFT amount blank + LEFT unit = the product
    stock default; RIGHT amount = 1 + RIGHT unit = the recipe line unit — i.e. "[__] {default} = 1 {unit}".

    Alpine contract (reads from the host's draft object):
      draft.needsConversion     — controls x-if on the outer template (DOM truly absent when false,
                                   so strict-mode Playwright locators never find the extra inputs)
      draft.productName         — product display name (e.g. "Cashews")
      draft.unitId              — the chosen recipe-line unit id
      draft.defaultUnitId       — the product's default (stock) unit id
      draft.defaultUnitCode     — the product's default unit code (e.g. "g")
      draft.stockUnits          — [{id, code, factorToBase}] units on the product stock dimension (LEFT)
      draft.recipeUnits         — [{id, code, factorToBase}] units on the recipe-line dimension (RIGHT)
      draft.convLeftAmount / draft.convLeftUnitId   — two-way bound to the LEFT amount + unit
      draft.convRightAmount / draft.convRightUnitId — two-way bound to the RIGHT amount + unit
      unitLabel(id)             — host helper: unitId → code string
      conversionEcho()          — host helper: derived stock-terms line, or '' while amounts incomplete

    Why x-if (template) not x-show: x-show renders the inputs but hides them with CSS, so a
    Playwright strict-mode locator("input[type='number']") would find them and break existing E2E
    tests that expect exactly one number input in the sheet. x-if only inserts the children when
    truthy — the amount inputs are genuinely absent from the DOM until a conversion is actually needed.

    The "Measure in {default} instead" escape sets draft.unitId = draft.defaultUnitId, which clears
    the $watch trigger and removes this block from the DOM.
*@

<template x-if="draft.needsConversion">
    <div style="margin-top:var(--space-4);padding:var(--space-3) var(--space-4);background:var(--color-surface-2);border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:var(--radius-md)">
        <p style="margin:0 0 var(--space-2);font-size:var(--font-size-sm)">
            Plantry stocks <strong x-text="draft.productName"></strong> in <strong x-text="draft.defaultUnitCode"></strong>.
            How does 1 <span x-text="unitLabel(draft.unitId)"></span> relate?
        </p>

        @* Two-sided equation (LEFT stock dimension = RIGHT recipe-line dimension) + derived echo —
           shared partial (plantry-pqlo). Each select is axis-locked, so no cross-dimension pair is
           possible. The escape button + saved-to-catalog note below stay here (sheet-specific).
           Model built in a code block because EchoShowExpression contains single quotes that would
           clash with a single-quoted model='...' attribute. *@
        @{
            var conversionEquation = new Plantry.Web.Pages.Shared.ConversionEquationViewModel
            {
                Root = "draft",
                EchoExpression = "conversionEcho()",
                EchoShowExpression = "conversionEcho() !== ''",
            };
        }
        <partial name="Shared/_ConversionEquation" model="conversionEquation" />

        <p style="margin:var(--space-2) 0 var(--space-2);font-size:var(--font-size-sm);color:var(--color-text-muted)">
            Use any amounts and units you know — saved to your catalog, so every future recipe reuses it.
        </p>
        <button type="button"
                class="btn btn--ghost btn--sm"
                @@click="draft.unitId = draft.defaultUnitId; draft.needsConversion = false; draft.convLeftAmount = ''; draft.convRightAmount = ''; draft.convFor = ''">
            Measure in <span x-text="draft.defaultUnitCode"></span> instead
        </button>
    </div>
</template>
